A fisheye lens might be a bit too ambitious for a birdhouse.
We learn from our mistakes.
I should have known, since I already made one with a "normal" lens.
I'll tell you more about it this weekend when I install the second one I made.
Let's say that the birds will have better internet than I did in 2015.
Or at least, that's the goal.
The box that already contains a nichoir benefits from the house's WiFi.
There's still work to do to connect the other one.
Well, I hung the other nichoir during the day. Here's what it looks like in a good spot in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside it," don't I hear ask.
At the top is one of those ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I retrieved from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has an odd shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it that way and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the entire setup is powered by a solar panel and a 18650 battery with a capacity of 2,600 mAh.
I haven't photographed the battery or the charger, but here is a picture of the solar panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the birdhouse houses the battery.
Fully charged, it gives me about 4 hours of energy.
I call this a feature. So the birds can also have a bit of privacy.
Initially, I wasn't sure if the internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this installation. The old access points that I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to mount a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof and point it down at the garden.
I could always do it when I install more camera birdhouses, especially in areas far from the house, I might need them.
Now, for reasons that elude me for now, the camera is offline. It turned off just an hour after sunset.
The battery charging may have stopped three hours before sunset due to a lack of light.
Maybe it couldn't fully charge in just under half a day.
I'll see how things play out tomorrow.
I don't have a battery telemetry system. I might add one in a future revision.
A few more sensors would be good, I think.
And perhaps a battery that can last all night, at least on paper.
Oh, and another lens.
The fisheye is way too wide.
But I am already looking at parts on Digikey, so I might just get a custom PCB made for this use.
Or not. We shall see.
And, it is still offline.
Great.
Given the solar panels installed on the house, the sun is really high for only about 90 minutes.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens or not.
Still offline.
Nothing is ever simple.
In fact, on the USB-C board I was using to plug in the battery charger, the 5V and ground were reversed.
I switched the wires, and now I have a charging indicator.
The ESP did not connect right away; let's wait a few minutes.
An hour later: still offline.
It seems to be rebooting in a loop and triggering the Tasmota reset functionality.
I think the panel is just trash. I ordered a bigger one, hoping it will work.
Look what I found in the workshop.
A 24V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is so low (and partly hidden behind a tree) that it drops almost to nothing as soon as I use it.
I think I'll wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this installation or if I need the best panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it should generate 12V at a maximum of 1.2A.
So either something is wrong with this panel or with my multimeter, or they have changed the specifications.
Good news everyone!
They have changed the specifications and mine is defective.
The titles of both old and new specifications mention a 12V, 10W panel.
That's why I don't delete my old emails.
Look: the thing reconnected for about half a minute about an hour ago.
Maybe the panel charged the battery just enough for 38 seconds of energy. It would have taken only a little more than two hours.
Guess what: it's cloudy today. So I'm not sure that this solar panel (probably broken) is able to generate enough energy to do anything.
Let's see.
Last update: I installed the new panel and it seems to be working.
It might shut down at sunset, but let's see.
By the way, I use Home Assistant's ping integration to check if it's connected or not.
The round-trip time is 102 ms. Not great, but not terrible.
